  "text": "In order to profile gene groups we require four data sources: a test group of genes (e.g. up-regulated genes), a reference group (e.g. all significantly expressed genes), GO annotations for these genes, and the Gene Ontology. Many chip-manufacturers provide GO annotations for the genes covered by their chips (e.g. Affymetrix (TM), see [21] ), otherwise gene groups can be annotated using tools like HomGL [CITATION_1] . The current version of the Gene Ontology can be downloaded from the website of the Gene Ontology Consortium [23] . In this analysis we used the Gene Ontology as of 11th February, 2004. The Gene Ontology can be represented as a directed acyclic graph (DAG) where the nodes represent the terms [CITATION_2] . Annotations are usually given as terms within the DAG implying a series of more general annotations upward in the GO graph, as illustrated in Figure 1 .",
